org.apache.sis.metadata.iso

Class DefaultIdentifier

  • Object
    • AbstractMetadata
      • ModifiableMetadata
        • ISOMetadata
          • DefaultIdentifier
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Serializable, Cloneable, Emptiable, LenientComparable, IdentifiedObject, Identifier

    public class DefaultIdentifier
extends ISOMetadata
implements Identifier
    Value uniquely identifying an object within a namespace. One or more Identifier instances can be associated to some metadata objects like operation, platform, instrument, event, processing, source, image description, geographic description and more.

    Referencing objects like coordinate system axis, geodetic datum, geographic CRS and more rather use an Identifier sub-interface, namely ReferenceIdentifier. The later is implemented in SIS by ImmutableIdentifier, which is a class unrelated to the usual org.apache.metadata hierarchy because of the immutable nature of referencing objects.

    Text, URN and XML representations
    The XML representation of DefaultIdentifier is similar to the ImmutableIdentifier one except for the "MD_" prefix. Example: 
    <gmd:MD_Identifier>
  <gmd:code>
    <gco:CharacterString>4326</gco:CharacterString>
  </gmd:code>
  <gmd:authority>
    <gmd:CI_Citation>
      <gmd:title>
        <gco:CharacterString>EPSG</gco:CharacterString>
      </gmd:title>
    </gmd:CI_Citation>
  </gmd:authority>
</gmd:MD_Identifier>
    See Also:
    ImmutableIdentifier, Serialized Form

    • Method Detail

      • castOrCopy

        public static DefaultIdentifier castOrCopy(Identifier object)
        Returns a SIS metadata implementation with the values of the given arbitrary implementation. This method performs the first applicable action in the following choices:
        • If the given object is null, then this method returns null.
        • Otherwise if the given object is already an instance of DefaultIdentifier, then it is returned unchanged.
        • Otherwise a new DefaultIdentifier instance is created using the copy constructor and returned. Note that this is a shallow copy operation, since the other metadata contained in the given object are not recursively copied.
        Parameters:
        object - The object to get as a SIS implementation, or null if none.
        Returns:
        A SIS implementation containing the values of the given object (may be the given object itself), or null if the argument was null.
